carrying on -- and these were all the ones known

00:01:56.110 --> 00:02:00.179
back in the day, and we since found more of these perfect numbers, and they're wonderful.

00:02:00.399 --> 00:02:06.718
But the reason we found them is because of our friends, Mersenne primes, which of course [are] another staple of Numberphile

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:12.839
So let's switch colors. So, Mersenne primes are 2 to the n minus 1,

00:02:13.750 --> 00:02:15.750
where that equals a prime number.

00:02:16.450 --> 00:02:19.620
So -- so that equals some prime because not all

00:02:20.710 --> 00:02:26.460
2 to the n's minus ones give you a prime, in fact, let's run through a few very quickly.

00:02:26.590 --> 00:02:31.380
So if I come over here, these are going to be my values of n. These are going to be my

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:33.839
2 to the n's minus ones,

00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:40.980
As if I start when n is 1 so that's going to be 2 minus 1, that equals 1, is that prime?

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:42.080
(Brady:) No.

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:44.180
Well, there's a whole argument to be had there...

00:02:46.180 --> 00:02:52.500
Sometimes it is, sometimes it isn't -- generally speaking, no, that doesn't count, ok, let's do n is 2, ok.

00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:57.380
So that's 2 squared, that's 4, minus 1 is 3, that is prime, awesome.

00:02:57.390 --> 00:03:04.619
Ok next one up, 3, that gives us 7, that is prime, brilliant, ok 4, 4 gives us

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:10.439
15: not prime. That doesn't work, so as you can see as we go along, some of them work,

00:03:11.050 --> 00:03:18.059
31, brilliant! That gets to stay, some of them don't -- 6, that gives us 63, no good,

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:19.450
right, and so,

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:25.540
some, but not all values of n [with] 2 [to the] n minus 1 give us a prime number out the other side, and some people

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:28.400
like looking for patterns and we call those people

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:31.529
"mathematicians" and so some people are like: "well, hang on,

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:34.380
this is only working when n is prime."

00:03:34.630 --> 00:03:39.630
Didn't work for one, not prime, two and three work because they are prime, didn't work for four, not prime, prime,

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:44.780
not prime, prime, and so on, and so in fact, if you try it for eight, it won't work, because that's

00:03:44.780 --> 00:03:50.420
255, not prime, won't work for nine because that's

00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:53.880
511, which looks very prime-y.

00:03:54.100 --> 00:04:00.600
That's got a real prime feel to it, not prime, in fact, when we check in 10 -- people get very --

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:06.500
I mean, 1023, I mean that looks like it's got a bit of prime going on that. It's not prime.

